WEBVTT

00:09.557 --> 00:11.933
(indistinct chatter)

00:39.432 --> 00:42.015
(microphone feedback)

00:42.099 --> 00:44.474
Bob Spicer: Well, thank you,
 thank you all,

00:44.557 --> 00:47.516
parents and town
advocates alike,

00:47.599 --> 00:50.933
for joining us on
this very special evening.

00:52.015 --> 00:53.766
We're here tonight to kick off

00:53.849 --> 00:56.557
our most ambitious
school year yet.

00:57.683 --> 01:00.265
We've run the numbers,
and folks,

01:00.349 --> 01:03.599
there's no simpler way
for me to put it.

01:03.683 --> 01:07.057
Our children
are getting smarter.

01:07.140 --> 01:09.474
(laughter)

01:09.557 --> 01:14.516
Harvard, two.
Dartmouth, two.

01:14.599 --> 01:16.891
Yale, three.

01:16.974 --> 01:18.849
U Penn, seven.

01:19.599 --> 01:21.015
Thank you.

01:21.099 --> 01:23.057
(man continues indistinct)

01:23.140 --> 01:25.599
(mutters)

01:30.140 --> 01:32.474
(mutters)

01:32.808 --> 01:33.808
(sniffs)

01:33.891 --> 01:36.099
(classical music playing)

01:43.015 --> 01:46.057
(man continues indistinct)

01:46.140 --> 01:48.724
...and my fellow trustees

01:48.808 --> 01:51.307
who wait all year long

01:51.391 --> 01:54.224
ranking the top
public schools in America

01:54.307 --> 01:57.849
based on SATs and college
acceptance rates.

01:58.599 --> 02:00.933
And Roslyn is four...

02:01.182 --> 02:03.349
(cheers and applause)

02:06.349 --> 02:08.515
And now, I'd like to bring out
the man responsible.

02:08.598 --> 02:09.973
-Congratulations.
-Thank you.

02:10.056 --> 02:11.599
In his ten years here,

02:11.683 --> 02:14.057
he's revamped
our education system.

02:14.140 --> 02:16.641
From pre-K all the way
to high school.

02:17.265 --> 02:20.015
Please join me in welcoming
to the stage

02:20.099 --> 02:22.974
our district superintendent
and my friend,

02:23.057 --> 02:24.724
Frank Tassone.

02:25.224 --> 02:26.974
(cheers and applause)

02:27.057 --> 02:29.015
(stirring music)

02:29.099 --> 02:32.224
♪ ♪

02:51.015 --> 02:54.182
♪ ♪

02:59.599 --> 03:01.224
(brakes hiss)

03:07.099 --> 03:08.307
Good morning.

03:10.307 --> 03:11.599
Hey there, good morning.

03:12.265 --> 03:13.516
Go Bulldogs.

03:13.599 --> 03:15.557
Frank:
 Have we heard about
 Mr. Kopple?

03:15.641 --> 03:16.891
-Wife had twins.
-Twins!

03:16.974 --> 03:18.474
-Late last night.
-Nice. Send over flowers

03:18.557 --> 03:20.099
and maybe
an edible arrangement.

03:20.182 --> 03:21.683
Can we, can we get
these things out of here?

03:21.766 --> 03:23.349
-Oh, they're nice for morale.
-Yeah, it'd be even nicer

03:23.432 --> 03:24.516
if they were
shaped like ones.

03:24.599 --> 03:26.015
-Pam: You know, Dr. Tassone--
-Hey.

03:26.099 --> 03:28.766
A wise woman once said
it's not having what you want.

03:28.849 --> 03:31.099
-It's wanting what you got.
-Mrs. Gluckin.

03:31.182 --> 03:33.683
I barely recognize you anymore
what with the new name,

03:33.766 --> 03:35.140
new office, new job title.

03:35.224 --> 03:37.474
The same pay, same paperwork.

03:37.724 --> 03:39.224
July and August
are all settled up.

03:39.307 --> 03:41.140
-Expenses booked and archived.
-Perfect.

03:41.224 --> 03:42.641
And something else I wanted
to talk to you about...

03:42.724 --> 03:44.224
Safety gates
are all taken care of.

03:44.307 --> 03:46.641
I'm meeting with City Hall
later today to go over strategy.

03:46.724 --> 03:48.057
Jeez, someone's
had their coffee.

03:48.140 --> 03:49.557
-Yeah.
-Jenny: Uh, Dr. Tassone?

03:49.641 --> 03:51.015
-Yeah.
-Uh, did you want your flight

03:51.099 --> 03:53.391
to the Vegas conference Friday
out of JFK or Newark?

03:53.474 --> 03:55.140
Thanks, J.
Whatever's cheaper works fine.

03:55.224 --> 03:57.140
And, uh, Mary Ann,
is there any way

03:57.224 --> 03:58.432
you'd be able to grab
my diet smoothie?

03:58.516 --> 03:59.849
-I was running late.
-Mary Ann: Oh, sure.

03:59.933 --> 04:01.391
-Uh, but there's
one more thing.
-Frank: Uh-huh.

04:01.474 --> 04:03.057
Carol Schweitzer's
been camped up

04:03.140 --> 04:04.808
in the conference room
since 6:30.

04:04.891 --> 04:06.057
Says it's urgent
she speaks with you.

04:06.140 --> 04:07.891
Okay, okay. Um...

04:07.974 --> 04:09.808
-Chad.
-Chad, Chad Schweitzer's...

04:09.891 --> 04:11.307
okay, I'll take care of it.

04:11.683 --> 04:13.015
-Thanks.
-Good luck.

04:13.099 --> 04:14.265
Stop it.

04:14.557 --> 04:15.683
Do us all a favor.

04:15.766 --> 04:18.140
If he's not out of there
in an hour, call 911.

04:18.808 --> 04:19.891
(chuckles)

04:19.974 --> 04:21.224
Carol:
And I am banging down doors

04:21.307 --> 04:22.265
until somebody here

04:22.349 --> 04:24.182
takes me seriously.
All right?

04:24.265 --> 04:27.265
That Militzok,
she plays favorites, okay?

04:27.349 --> 04:29.099
She wouldn't even let him
take a bathroom break

04:29.182 --> 04:32.057
during the test,
and he has
a hyperactive bladder.

04:32.140 --> 04:33.766
Chad, honey,
tell him how you...

04:33.849 --> 04:35.891
you know what, I have a note
here from his doctor, okay?

04:35.974 --> 04:37.766
Ms. Schweitzer,
just, just calm down.

04:37.849 --> 04:40.099
-Let's, let's just--
-No one will listen to me.

04:40.182 --> 04:41.891
All right, I don't know
what else I'm supposed to do.

04:41.974 --> 04:44.808
Chad, he is just as gifted
as everyone else in his year.

04:44.891 --> 04:46.474
-Absolutely.
-And...

04:46.557 --> 04:48.224
I'm scared, Dr. Tassone,

04:48.307 --> 04:50.641
because if he
doesn't get into OMNI...

04:52.015 --> 04:53.891
and he starts to think
of himself as less than...

04:53.974 --> 04:55.391
No, no, no, no, no, no, no.

04:55.724 --> 04:57.099
No, I will talk
to Ms. Militzok.

04:57.182 --> 04:59.182
I will straighten
this whole thing out.

04:59.265 --> 05:00.474
-You will?
-Yes.

05:00.557 --> 05:02.849
And, and we'll just set
a make-up test for Chad.

05:02.933 --> 05:04.641
All right, with ample
bathroom time.

05:05.015 --> 05:06.140
Thank you, Dr. Tassone.

05:06.224 --> 05:07.849
I can't tell you how much
I appreciate that.

05:07.974 --> 05:09.307
There's no need to thank me,
all right?

05:09.391 --> 05:11.307
Chad's a smart kid with
the world ahead of him,

05:11.391 --> 05:13.224
and it's our job
to give him the runway.

05:14.474 --> 05:15.516
Thank you.

05:20.224 --> 05:21.391
It's funny.

05:22.140 --> 05:24.182
You know, Chad,
when I was your age,

05:24.683 --> 05:26.808
I didn't even place
into fast track math.

05:26.891 --> 05:27.808
-Really?
-No.

05:27.891 --> 05:29.307
I couldn't nail
my times tables.

05:29.391 --> 05:32.557
And at the time,
I thought my world was ending.

05:32.641 --> 05:35.724
But I caught up.
You know what?

05:37.391 --> 05:39.265
Now I set the math curriculum.

05:44.349 --> 05:46.182
(light orchestral music)

05:46.265 --> 05:49.391
♪ ♪

05:57.933 --> 05:59.099
(exhales)

06:08.265 --> 06:10.057
(knocking)

06:15.432 --> 06:16.933
Can I help you with something?

06:17.641 --> 06:19.265
Oh, no, it's okay.

06:19.599 --> 06:21.974
I'm just here
for Mrs. Cremona.

06:22.057 --> 06:23.599
-Or Gluckin.
-Ooh, she's not here,

06:23.683 --> 06:25.849
but I'm more than happy
to answer any questions if...

06:25.933 --> 06:27.724
-Really? That would...
-Mm-hmm, yeah.

06:27.808 --> 06:29.432
I don't wanna bother you
if you're busy, but--

06:29.516 --> 06:30.808
No, come on in, bother me.

06:30.891 --> 06:33.224
I'm doing spreadsheets.
Come, come in.

06:33.307 --> 06:35.724
Take a seat.
Uh...

06:36.432 --> 06:38.182
I don't think we've
had a chance to meet.

06:38.265 --> 06:39.432
-It's Rachel.
-Rachel, right.

06:39.516 --> 06:40.933
Neil's little sister.

06:41.474 --> 06:43.557
Yeah.
Wow, good memory.

06:43.641 --> 06:46.140
I hope he's keeping
out of trouble
over at Northwestern.

06:46.224 --> 06:48.516
Yeah, he loves it.
He's doing bio-chem.

06:48.599 --> 06:50.766
Ah, well, they have
great journalism there, too.

06:51.474 --> 06:52.641
Yes, they do.

06:53.307 --> 06:54.599
-(chuckles)
-Um...

06:54.683 --> 06:57.140
okay, so they just,
they want me
to write an article

06:57.224 --> 06:59.641
about the SkyWalk proposal
in the new budget.

06:59.724 --> 07:03.307
And I just need a pull quote
from administration.

07:03.391 --> 07:06.349
Yeah, oh, okay.
A sound bite, nice.

07:06.766 --> 07:08.474
Um...
(clears throat)

07:09.349 --> 07:10.724
We've been
asking high schoolers

07:10.808 --> 07:12.182
how we can make
their day easier,

07:12.265 --> 07:15.933
so we came up with this idea,
the SkyWalk.

07:16.015 --> 07:20.015
Um, a bridge,
to link the school
from end to end.

07:20.683 --> 07:23.974
And um, it's a
huge undertaking for us.

07:24.057 --> 07:25.599
And we can't wait
to break ground

07:25.683 --> 07:28.182
once the plans
are approved next May.

07:29.933 --> 07:32.265
Great, that's all I need.
Thank you so much.

07:32.349 --> 07:34.057
That's it?
No, no follow-ups?

07:34.140 --> 07:36.349
No, it's just a puff piece.

07:36.432 --> 07:38.724
They save the real stories
for seniors.

07:39.140 --> 07:40.140
Rachel.

07:41.933 --> 07:45.683
It's only a puff piece
if you let it be a puff piece.

07:46.224 --> 07:47.349
Oh, uh...

07:47.683 --> 07:49.808
That's what they'll tell you
over at Northwestern.

07:50.683 --> 07:52.182
All right?
A real journalist

07:52.265 --> 07:55.015
can turn any assignment
into a story.

07:59.099 --> 08:01.974
Are you busy?
Just a couple of colleagues
want to convey thanks.

08:02.057 --> 08:04.933
Rachel Bhargava, staff writer
for the "Hilltop Beacon."

08:05.015 --> 08:08.182
Uh, this is Bob Spicer,
school board president.

08:08.265 --> 08:09.474
-Hi. Oh, you're, uh...
-Hey.

08:09.557 --> 08:10.933
you're in my daughter,
Becca's year, right?

08:11.015 --> 08:13.057
-Mm-hmm.
-Say hi to your dad for me.

08:13.265 --> 08:14.933
Nice to meet you, Rachel.
And if you want to

08:15.015 --> 08:17.391
follow up, just set a time
with Mary Ann, okay?

08:18.349 --> 08:21.557
And, uh, I'll be keeping
an eye out for your byline.

08:24.808 --> 08:27.307
The demand is insane.
It's skyrocketing.

08:27.391 --> 08:29.849
We're seeing three bedrooms
go for over a million
in Roslyn Heights.

08:29.933 --> 08:31.724
Yeah, you just don't
see those kinds of numbers

08:31.808 --> 08:33.140
in Syosset or Jericho.

08:33.224 --> 08:35.307
Right, but those towns are
a further commute from the city.

08:35.390 --> 08:36.808
Not Manhasset, not Great Neck.

08:36.890 --> 08:39.099
It's the public schools.
The better the school system,

08:39.182 --> 08:40.933
the higher the price tag
on the homes, period.

08:41.015 --> 08:43.557
Bob:
Our firm has sold nine
separate lots in that area

08:43.640 --> 08:45.099
since the report in
that journal came out.

08:45.182 --> 08:46.766
And, uh,
here's a little something

08:46.849 --> 08:49.224
-you know, from all of us.
-Frank: Okay.

08:50.057 --> 08:53.265
Oh, wow.
Really, that's, oh, wow.

08:53.891 --> 08:55.849
-Keep up the good work.
-Well, thanks, everyone.

08:55.933 --> 08:57.307
-Dr. Tassone?
-Oh, yeah.

08:57.391 --> 08:58.641
-Do you mind
if we get a little--
-Yeah, yeah, yeah.

08:58.724 --> 09:00.140
-Something for my office.
-Great.

09:00.224 --> 09:01.891
-I really appreciate you...
-Scoot in, scoot in, Will.

09:01.974 --> 09:03.849
-...coming in today.
-Mm-hmm.

09:03.933 --> 09:05.057
Thank you, okay.

09:05.432 --> 09:06.265
(shutter snaps)

09:06.349 --> 09:07.391
-Okay, thank you.
-Okay.

09:07.474 --> 09:08.641
-All right?
-Yeah, let's let him--

09:08.724 --> 09:09.808
-Let him get back to work.
-Thank you.

09:09.891 --> 09:11.140
-No, I really appreciate it.
-Yeah.

09:11.224 --> 09:12.933
-Thank you so much.
-Thank you.

09:13.015 --> 09:14.557
Okay.

09:17.849 --> 09:19.974
I can't eat these.
Just, if you put them out

09:20.057 --> 09:22.182
for everybody to pick at,
that'd be great.

09:23.766 --> 09:25.307
They were out of the flax seed.

09:27.057 --> 09:29.140
That's okay, that's okay.
Thanks.

09:30.015 --> 09:31.307
(slurps)

09:33.140 --> 09:34.641
How much do you
figure a guy like Bob

09:34.724 --> 09:36.140
makes at his regular job?

09:36.474 --> 09:38.265
-Pam: Bob Spicer, you mean?
-Mm-hmm.

09:38.641 --> 09:39.974
Oh...

09:40.516 --> 09:42.307
high sixes a year, minimum.

09:42.724 --> 09:44.224
Maybe seven figures
in this market.

09:44.307 --> 09:46.516
-Why?
-Oh, forget it.

09:50.391 --> 09:51.599
You look tired.

09:51.808 --> 09:52.891
(sighs)

09:52.974 --> 09:54.683
You might wanna
go home early,
get some rest.

09:54.766 --> 09:56.140
I gotta run Dickens.

09:56.474 --> 09:57.891
Maybe I'll try
and bow out and

09:57.974 --> 09:59.724
get a headstart
and early prep for
Vegas this weekend.

09:59.808 --> 10:01.599
-I wouldn't bail on book club.
-Why?

10:01.683 --> 10:02.683
Those women adore you,

10:02.766 --> 10:04.557
and each one talks
to two dozen more.

10:05.057 --> 10:07.057
The next budget vote's
only nine months away.

10:07.349 --> 10:09.599
-Right, our SkyWalk.
-Yeah, the SkyWalk is big.

10:09.683 --> 10:11.683
Gets us to first.
That's all that matters.

10:14.599 --> 10:15.683
(slurps)

10:16.182 --> 10:18.015
This new diet is kicking my ass.

10:18.099 --> 10:19.224
What is that, even?

10:20.015 --> 10:21.432
It's got charcoal in it
or something like that.

10:21.516 --> 10:22.516
Yeah, coal.

10:23.057 --> 10:25.474
I would kill somebody
for a carb right now.

10:26.265 --> 10:27.891
I don't know
where you could find one.

10:28.474 --> 10:29.974
You are such a bitch.

10:31.015 --> 10:32.391
Oh, would you like a bite?

10:33.641 --> 10:34.974
-I hate pastrami on rye.
-You want a bite.

10:35.057 --> 10:36.599
-I hate pastrami on rye.
-Yeah, I know you hate it.

10:36.683 --> 10:38.432
-Open up.
-(moans)

10:38.516 --> 10:40.516
-Fucking so good.
-Right?

10:40.599 --> 10:41.849
Come on, you can eat more.

10:42.391 --> 10:43.974
You got-- come on,
one more bite.

10:44.057 --> 10:45.307
-I will kill you.
-I won't tell anyone.

10:45.391 --> 10:46.432
I'm not gonna tell anyone.

10:46.516 --> 10:47.557
(bright orchestral music)

10:47.641 --> 10:49.349
-(laughs)
-You're a growing boy.

10:49.432 --> 10:52.099
Come on.
Eat the fuckin' sandwich.

10:52.182 --> 10:55.265
♪ ♪

11:04.224 --> 11:06.641
(indistinct chatter)

11:06.724 --> 11:07.724
Frank:
Let's get started.

11:07.808 --> 11:09.265
Should we get started,
everyone?

11:09.516 --> 11:12.432
Uh, what do we all think
of "Martin Chuzzlewit"?

11:18.766 --> 11:20.182
Okay.
Um...

11:21.474 --> 11:24.265
You know, Frank, the culture
is not for everyone.

11:24.349 --> 11:25.641
Eh, I thought we
wound up having a

11:25.724 --> 11:27.766
really good
discussion, ultimately.

11:31.182 --> 11:32.307
Um...

11:34.933 --> 11:37.432
Frank, can I ask you
a personal question?

11:38.140 --> 11:39.307
Sure.

11:39.974 --> 11:41.599
It's just that...

11:42.182 --> 11:43.307
Jonah's...

11:43.724 --> 11:46.641
you know, having a really
hard time with the separation.

11:46.724 --> 11:48.391
Yeah.
You know, Ms. Schlacter,

11:48.474 --> 11:51.766
uh, told me that he's opened up
a little bit in Banana Splits?

11:53.307 --> 11:55.391
-Right, yeah, oh, my God.
-Yeah.

11:55.599 --> 11:58.474
-Thank you for getting him in.
-No, of course.

11:59.557 --> 12:01.891
It has been
so hard on us, and...

12:02.224 --> 12:03.766
-Yeah.
-You have been...

12:04.808 --> 12:06.224
such a tremendous help.

12:06.307 --> 12:09.766
Oh, Sharon, of course.
Anytime, anytime.

12:10.891 --> 12:12.349
Yeah, and...

12:13.474 --> 12:14.474
Um...

12:18.182 --> 12:20.432
-Frank, I'm sorry.
-No, no, no, no, no.

12:20.516 --> 12:21.641
You want what's best
for your son.

12:21.724 --> 12:23.057
That's nothing to be ashamed of.

12:23.140 --> 12:25.265
Uh, no, it makes you strong.
It's, um...

12:26.974 --> 12:28.140
(exhales)
I...

12:28.516 --> 12:30.349
you know, I think
at the end of the day,

12:30.766 --> 12:32.641
her memory is still very fresh.

12:37.474 --> 12:38.766
(Pam sighs)

12:38.849 --> 12:40.808
Ay-yi-yi-yi-yi.

12:45.474 --> 12:47.599
Somehow, I'm not surprised.

12:47.683 --> 12:49.474
Jenny screwed up
some paperwork earlier.

12:49.557 --> 12:50.891
I'm saving her ass.

12:50.974 --> 12:52.557
Jenny's got a good aunt.

12:53.099 --> 12:54.557
How did Dickens go?

12:54.933 --> 12:56.099
(chuckles)

12:56.432 --> 12:58.974
Well, it was Sharon Katz's
place this week.

13:00.766 --> 13:02.307
And...
(laughs)

13:05.349 --> 13:07.140
-I knew it.
-I, I think maybe

13:07.224 --> 13:08.933
I shouldn't have offered
to wash up.

13:09.015 --> 13:10.849
(chuckles)
That poor woman.

13:11.683 --> 13:13.140
She's nowhere near your type.

13:13.391 --> 13:15.099
She's not, she's not.

13:15.182 --> 13:17.140
(laughter)

13:17.224 --> 13:19.099
-Jamieson.
-Uh, Honors English.

13:19.182 --> 13:20.933
-Loves Nietzsche.
-Very good.

13:21.015 --> 13:22.724
-Yep.
-Uh, DiGennaro?

13:23.474 --> 13:25.766
Oh, DiGennaro.
Uh...

13:25.849 --> 13:27.766
(clears throat)
Social studies,

13:28.099 --> 13:29.766
-ninth grade global hist--
-Ah!

13:30.391 --> 13:32.140
-Oh, American history.
-Uh-huh.

13:32.224 --> 13:35.015
Uh, coaches Little League, too.

13:35.099 --> 13:36.307
-Mm-hmm.
-Yes.

13:36.391 --> 13:38.140
Well, these are too easy.
Oh, here's a toughie.

13:38.224 --> 13:39.557
Uh-huh.

13:41.057 --> 13:42.057
Todhunter.

13:42.641 --> 13:43.724
Oh, shit.

13:46.724 --> 13:49.265
Todhunter, Todhunter...

13:52.599 --> 13:53.891
Mr. Todhunter.

13:53.974 --> 13:56.057
How's that bowling league
shaping up this season?

13:56.140 --> 13:58.057
Oh, uh, we're ahead.

13:58.891 --> 14:01.099
But we've got our big match
against Jericho on Sunday.

14:01.182 --> 14:03.724
Jericho, mm.
I think you'll crush them.

14:03.808 --> 14:05.140
Thank you for putting this on.

14:05.224 --> 14:06.516
-This is so nice.
-Oh, of course.
My pleasure.

14:06.599 --> 14:07.766
-Man: Oh, Frank!
-The least I could do.

14:07.849 --> 14:09.057
-Yeah, excuse me.
-Man: Hey, Frank.

14:10.391 --> 14:11.474
-Hey.
-So, um...

14:11.557 --> 14:13.432
hey, are you getting
pumped for Vegas?

14:13.516 --> 14:15.015
'Cause, uh,
I got my bags packed.

14:15.099 --> 14:16.224
-I'm ready to go.
-Yeah.

14:16.307 --> 14:17.474
It'll be good to get away
from the wife

14:17.557 --> 14:18.724
for a few days too, huh?

14:18.808 --> 14:20.182
-Right?
-Right.

14:20.265 --> 14:21.432
(chuckling)

14:21.516 --> 14:23.933
-A few days, yeah.
-(clears throat)

14:24.015 --> 14:26.224
You want to know how many bids
we got from contractors?

14:26.307 --> 14:28.516
Mm-hmm, for
the SkyWalk construction.

14:28.599 --> 14:30.599
You explored several options,
right?

14:31.432 --> 14:34.599
-I think we had four or five.
-Okay.

14:34.933 --> 14:36.557
Rachel:
From which firms, exactly?

14:36.641 --> 14:38.140
Hang-hang on a sec.
What's this article

14:38.224 --> 14:39.599
you're supposed to be writing?

14:40.432 --> 14:42.808
Oh, it's a piece
on the SkyWalk.

14:43.849 --> 14:45.516
And the student paper
wanted a deep dive

14:45.599 --> 14:47.099
into construction specs?

14:47.182 --> 14:49.766
They're giving me free reign,
more or less.

14:50.224 --> 14:52.307
I guess I'm just looking
for an interesting way in.

14:52.641 --> 14:54.516
-Oh, okay, Ruth.
-Rachel.

14:54.724 --> 14:57.516
Rachel, so let me give you
a great angle for your story.

14:57.599 --> 14:59.057
-Okay.
-You wanna write this down

14:59.140 --> 15:00.557
-or are you--
-I'm taping.

15:00.641 --> 15:02.015
Oh.

15:02.891 --> 15:04.015
Okay.

15:05.140 --> 15:07.349
The SkyWalk is a great project.

15:07.432 --> 15:10.099
It'll be the first SkyWalk
on all of Long Island,

15:10.182 --> 15:12.557
and yet one more reason
Roslyn schools

15:12.641 --> 15:14.641
put Jericho and Syosset
to shame.

15:14.724 --> 15:17.557
And it'll look great
and make all our lives easier.

15:17.641 --> 15:19.891
Thank you, the end.
Good night and good luck.

15:19.974 --> 15:21.349
What else can I help you with?

15:23.808 --> 15:25.432
Do you have the bids handy?

15:26.140 --> 15:27.307
Or are they not on you?

15:27.557 --> 15:29.349
No, they're not on me.
They're locked in the basement,

15:29.432 --> 15:30.974
lost in the annals of history.

15:31.683 --> 15:33.599
Well, I have next period free.

15:34.641 --> 15:36.057
(tense music begins)

15:36.641 --> 15:38.683
-Do you?
-Mm-hmm.

15:40.182 --> 15:41.557
All right.

15:42.265 --> 15:43.933
(drawer opens)

15:44.015 --> 15:45.683
Good luck finding 'em.

15:48.182 --> 15:50.224
(tense music continues)

15:50.307 --> 15:53.391
♪ ♪

16:13.974 --> 16:15.516
Jenny:
Do you need somethin'?

16:16.849 --> 16:18.557
Just a couple of photocopies.

16:20.432 --> 16:21.391
Okay.

16:21.891 --> 16:23.808
-So you're a sophomore?
-Junior.

16:23.891 --> 16:27.391
My son Jake is actually
in the second grade
over at Bellmore.

16:28.599 --> 16:30.349
You know,
not too far from here.

16:31.474 --> 16:33.724
-South Shore, you know.
-Mm.

16:43.891 --> 16:48.224
Oh, it's an old building.
We get leaks every so often.

16:49.099 --> 16:51.224
(water dripping)

16:54.140 --> 16:56.224
It usually stops after,
like, a minute.

16:57.432 --> 16:59.432
(upbeat music)

16:59.516 --> 17:02.599
♪ ♪

17:08.432 --> 17:10.391
(indistinct chatter)

17:11.973 --> 17:14.015
We need a hard eight here.
We need boxcars.

17:14.098 --> 17:16.057
We need boxcars,
Lenny, we need boxcars.

17:16.140 --> 17:17.973
(screaming and cheering)

17:19.766 --> 17:21.391
Speaker:
I know what
you're all thinking.

17:21.473 --> 17:24.432
At first glance, these numbers
might seem prohibitive

17:24.516 --> 17:27.432
but I'm here to tell you
that with some vision,

17:27.516 --> 17:29.974
they can dovetail
quite amicably.

17:30.057 --> 17:32.182
As we can see,
the added benefits

17:32.265 --> 17:34.849
to such a program
are remunerative.

17:34.933 --> 17:36.391
I'd love for you to see
what we're doing out there

17:36.474 --> 17:37.849
-if you're ever on Long Island.
-Yeah, I think,

17:37.933 --> 17:40.224
I think we're on the East Coast
in November, December.

17:40.307 --> 17:41.683
-So I'll--
-Well, we're there.

17:41.766 --> 17:43.099
-Good, good, good, good.
-Okay.

17:43.182 --> 17:44.474
And listen, stop by
and have a drink
before you leave.

17:44.557 --> 17:45.724
-All right?
-That was terrific.

17:45.808 --> 17:46.974
-Thank you.
-Take care.

17:50.808 --> 17:51.974
(smacks lips)

17:53.057 --> 17:54.099
Bartender: Great.

17:56.307 --> 17:57.516
All right.

17:58.140 --> 17:59.349
What can I get ya?

17:59.557 --> 18:01.724
Uh, just a club soda with lime.

18:01.808 --> 18:03.808
And can I see
your food menu, please?

18:07.474 --> 18:09.265
(liquid pouring)

18:16.349 --> 18:17.516
And...

18:21.933 --> 18:23.057
Frank: Kyle.

18:24.516 --> 18:25.849
Kyle Contreras.

18:28.474 --> 18:32.391
Plandome High
maybe 15 years ago, right?

18:32.933 --> 18:34.974
Yeah, I used to
teach English there.

18:35.641 --> 18:37.015
Dr. Tassone.

18:37.849 --> 18:39.015
Frank.

18:39.849 --> 18:41.516
-Frank.
-(scoffs)

18:42.391 --> 18:44.182
Kyle:
I would think that
you would forget

18:44.265 --> 18:45.933
about us the minute
we got out of there.

18:46.015 --> 18:47.766
Frank:
Oh, no,
you'd be surprised.

18:47.849 --> 18:49.474
I mean, some things
I wish I could forget.

18:49.557 --> 18:50.933
Kyle: Yeah.
You know somethin'

18:51.015 --> 18:53.224
I wish I could forget?
Would be Lippman's hair piece.

18:53.307 --> 18:54.599
Do you remember
that thing that--

18:54.683 --> 18:57.432
-(laughs)
-With the, with
the double swoop?

18:58.015 --> 19:00.724
Oh, my God, Lippman's
hair piece, Christ.

19:01.140 --> 19:03.683
So, what do you, what do you--

19:03.766 --> 19:05.474
are you teaching English
at the new place?

19:05.557 --> 19:07.724
No, I'm, I'm administrative now.

19:08.641 --> 19:09.557
Like a principal?

19:09.641 --> 19:11.849
No, like
superintendent of schools.

19:12.557 --> 19:14.516
Look at that.
You love saying that.

19:14.766 --> 19:17.182
You love that.
Superintendent of schools.

19:17.265 --> 19:19.224
-With the head, too.
-I've done it for 12 years.

19:19.307 --> 19:20.641
I mean, look, it's great.

19:20.724 --> 19:22.808
It does have its trade-offs,
like anything.

19:22.891 --> 19:24.432
I really miss being back
in the classroom

19:24.516 --> 19:26.557
sometimes with my students,
you know.

19:27.224 --> 19:29.766
How about you?
You, um, you still writing?

19:30.683 --> 19:32.224
Short stories, science fiction,
right?

19:32.307 --> 19:33.974
I remember you used
to carry around

19:34.057 --> 19:35.724
that beat-up copy
of "Dune" everywhere.

19:35.808 --> 19:38.307
Yeah, I mostly
just wrote that stuff

19:38.391 --> 19:39.683
to get out of your book reports.

19:39.766 --> 19:41.766
No, come on, come on.
There was that really good one

19:41.849 --> 19:44.099
about the, um,
about the alien colony.

19:44.307 --> 19:47.099
I talked about it in your rec
for Stony Brook, right?

19:47.724 --> 19:50.265
Yeah, yeah, for Stony Brook.

19:50.724 --> 19:51.933
(clears throat)

19:53.057 --> 19:54.641
Sorry, I, um...

19:54.849 --> 19:57.224
I burnt out at Stony Brook.

19:57.432 --> 19:58.974
After a few years, I...

20:00.015 --> 20:01.641
moved out here.

20:01.724 --> 20:03.307
Um...

20:03.974 --> 20:07.808
I was dancing
up until very recently.

20:08.224 --> 20:09.557
Dancing?

20:13.182 --> 20:14.265
Thank you.

20:16.140 --> 20:17.432
(sniffs)

20:21.599 --> 20:25.015
So does your wife
come with you
on these things, or...

20:25.099 --> 20:27.391
-Oh, um--
-Is she back in New York?

20:27.474 --> 20:29.307
No, no, no,
my wife passed away.

20:31.974 --> 20:32.849
Oh.

20:35.307 --> 20:36.974
-I'm sorry.
-No, no, it's...

20:37.474 --> 20:39.099
it's fine.
It was a long time ago.

20:40.391 --> 20:43.307
Um, it was before
I had you, even.

20:45.140 --> 20:46.140
Hm.

20:48.557 --> 20:49.808
How's the food?

20:50.057 --> 20:51.182
Shit.

20:51.265 --> 20:52.474
(laughs)

21:02.474 --> 21:03.974
You wanna try somewhere else?

21:17.057 --> 21:19.849
I thought you were here
for two days.

21:20.224 --> 21:22.015
Uh, just for the weekend, yeah.

21:22.849 --> 21:25.224
A lot of suits for a weekend.

21:25.307 --> 21:27.432
Well, you never know
what might come up these...

21:27.516 --> 21:29.015
Right.

21:29.766 --> 21:31.307
That was always your thing,
wasn't it?

21:31.391 --> 21:32.724
Even when you were
an English teacher,

21:32.808 --> 21:35.933
you were always
the guy in the suits.

21:36.015 --> 21:37.349
What's wrong with a suit?

21:38.349 --> 21:40.015
I don't know, it's just...

21:41.099 --> 21:42.140
it's a little sad.

21:42.224 --> 21:43.224
(laughs)

21:43.307 --> 21:44.974
Just a little sad.

21:47.265 --> 21:49.432
I think they put some bottles
in the, uh...

21:49.891 --> 21:51.265
in the bar fridge,
I'm not sure why.

21:51.349 --> 21:53.391
You're allowed to make
eye contact, Frank.

22:15.849 --> 22:16.891
Hey.

22:17.641 --> 22:18.766
No, I'm not.

22:20.391 --> 22:21.557
Right.

22:38.724 --> 22:40.766
(classic strings playing)

22:40.849 --> 22:43.933
♪ ♪

23:20.015 --> 23:21.516
Rachel: Dad!

23:23.974 --> 23:25.474
I got dinner.

23:37.391 --> 23:38.766
Anything happen today?

23:41.557 --> 23:44.432
I spoke to the
assistant superintendent.

23:45.140 --> 23:46.140
For an article.

23:46.599 --> 23:48.432
The woman who runs
all the business.

23:49.557 --> 23:50.599
Hm.

23:51.683 --> 23:54.057
Wonder if they're looking to
hire anybody in development.

23:54.557 --> 23:55.849
You're overqualified.

24:00.516 --> 24:02.516
(soft music playing)

24:02.599 --> 24:05.683
♪ ♪

24:28.474 --> 24:30.391
-Late night, Ms. Gluckin?
-(gasps)

24:30.474 --> 24:32.683
Jesus, Eddie,
you scared the shit out of me.

24:32.766 --> 24:34.265
Got any fun plans
for the weekend?

24:34.349 --> 24:36.432
Yeah, no, all I want is
to spend some quiet time

24:36.516 --> 24:37.516
at home with my kids.

24:37.599 --> 24:39.099
-You know.
-All right.

24:39.182 --> 24:40.391
Have a good time.

24:40.474 --> 24:41.808
-See you next week.
-Yeah, good night, Eddie.

24:41.891 --> 24:43.516
-Sorry about scare--
-That's all right.

24:46.140 --> 24:47.265
(exhales)

24:50.599 --> 24:52.432
(laughter)

24:54.432 --> 24:55.516
He's...

24:56.432 --> 24:58.808
Okay, first of all,
they're too small.

24:58.891 --> 25:01.182
Oh, girls, have you met
my niece, Jenny Aquila?

25:01.265 --> 25:03.432
She's working with me over
at Roslyn, district clerk.

25:03.516 --> 25:05.349
-Oh.
-Isn't this place beautiful?

25:05.432 --> 25:07.557
-I mean...
-So gorgeous.

25:07.891 --> 25:10.599
Howard must be making out like
a bandit with those Chevys.

25:10.683 --> 25:13.099
He's been consulting
a little on the side.

25:13.182 --> 25:14.933
I'm proud of him.

25:16.140 --> 25:19.057
We're planning a big remodel
once the season's
through, actually.

25:19.140 --> 25:21.599
Oh, wow.
Who's your contractor?

25:22.307 --> 25:23.849
-Jim: Ma, help!
-Pam: Jim Boy's gonna do it.

25:23.933 --> 25:26.099
Big goose down.
I can't-- Ah!

25:26.641 --> 25:30.265
Are you sure Jimmy's ready
to take on a project this size?

25:30.641 --> 25:32.015
Yeah, it'll be good for him.

25:32.224 --> 25:34.182
Get his mind going
on somethin' new.

25:34.265 --> 25:35.516
-Aunt Pam.
-Pam: Yeah?

25:35.599 --> 25:37.683
Uh, can I talk to you
inside just for a sec?

25:37.766 --> 25:38.849
Pam: Sure.

25:38.933 --> 25:40.766
All right, Jen.
What's going on?

25:41.182 --> 25:43.641
Uh, honestly...

25:44.182 --> 25:45.265
(scoffs)

25:45.349 --> 25:47.599
I feel bad even
bringing it up, but, um...

25:48.182 --> 25:50.307
-Jake's birthday is comin' up.
-Oh!

25:50.391 --> 25:53.849
And he's been asking for
the Sony PlayStation.

25:53.933 --> 25:55.391
-Video game system.
-Yeah.

25:55.474 --> 25:59.057
And how all his friends have it
and how he feels left out.

25:59.140 --> 26:01.140
-Aw.
-You know, um,

26:01.224 --> 26:04.516
money's been tight,
and I was just thinking since

26:04.599 --> 26:07.391
Howard's been doin'
so well and all--

26:07.474 --> 26:08.974
(blender whirring)

26:19.974 --> 26:22.099
I'd pay you back
as soon as I'm able.

26:24.140 --> 26:25.808
Just put it on the card.

26:28.599 --> 26:30.724
Pam:
Amber, sweetie, do you mind

26:30.808 --> 26:32.641
giving your cousin Jenny
and me a minute?

26:35.557 --> 26:36.808
Thank you.

26:38.099 --> 26:40.182
But I was wondering
if maybe you could
just lend me

26:40.265 --> 26:41.474
the money from
your personal...

26:41.557 --> 26:43.057
Don't worry about it.
It'll all be reconciled

26:43.140 --> 26:44.057
at the end of the month.

26:44.140 --> 26:45.683
I've been doing this
a long time.

26:47.057 --> 26:48.224
It's, it's just,

26:48.307 --> 26:50.099
he wants that PlayStation
so much, you know?

26:50.182 --> 26:52.099
Just put the receipt on my desk
first thing Monday morning

26:52.182 --> 26:53.891
and don't give it
another thought.

26:54.182 --> 26:57.349
Now if you'll excuse me,
I have to play host.

27:06.349 --> 27:07.891
I don't get this.
What is this?

27:08.766 --> 27:10.349
It's the SkyWalk piece
you wanted.

27:11.641 --> 27:14.307
No, this is two pages
of contractor bids,

27:14.391 --> 27:16.265
building materials,
and zoning ordinances

27:16.349 --> 27:17.808
in brutal detail.

27:17.891 --> 27:19.349
Yeah, it's journalism.

27:19.432 --> 27:20.599
Our readers are 15.

27:21.265 --> 27:24.140
You realize we have to submit
every issue to Bressler

27:24.224 --> 27:25.432
before we go to print.

27:25.891 --> 27:28.307
And Dr. Tassone,
and Pam Cremona.

27:28.391 --> 27:30.307
Pam Gluckin.
It's Gluckin now.

27:30.391 --> 27:33.391
Look, we're not
the "New York Times," right?

27:33.474 --> 27:35.808
We're an extracurricular.
We are a club

27:35.891 --> 27:37.808
designed to get us all
into good colleges.

27:38.224 --> 27:40.808
We have a certain
finesse to the way
we approach stories here.

27:40.891 --> 27:42.808
A je ne sais quoi,
if you will.

27:43.224 --> 27:46.224
But don't worry, though.
You're gonna get the hang of it.

27:48.724 --> 27:50.724
(soft music playing)

27:50.808 --> 27:53.891
♪ ♪

28:00.265 --> 28:02.391
(music brightens)

28:22.099 --> 28:24.224
♪ ♪

28:40.849 --> 28:41.974
(beep)

28:57.391 --> 28:58.808
(beeping)

29:03.557 --> 29:05.641
♪ ♪

29:07.307 --> 29:09.140
(beeping)

29:19.140 --> 29:20.349
Clerk: Sir.

29:21.391 --> 29:22.808
Could I ask, uh,

29:22.891 --> 29:24.933
how many of our stores
have you visited today?

29:25.265 --> 29:26.474
Uh...

29:27.140 --> 29:28.182
a couple.

29:28.265 --> 29:29.683
The ones in Farmingdale
and Islip

29:29.766 --> 29:31.057
didn't have what
I was looking for.

29:31.140 --> 29:32.849
I mean, you know,
we actually offer

29:32.933 --> 29:36.015
free ship-to service for
our high-value customers.

29:40.349 --> 29:41.849
You think I'm high-value?

29:42.557 --> 29:45.015
I mean, reasonably, yeah.

29:47.349 --> 29:48.849
So where's this stuff going?

29:51.349 --> 29:52.933
-Bob: Oh, shit.
-Lorraine: Yeah, no, no.

29:53.015 --> 29:54.724
-I'll get him.
No, he's right here.
-Bob: Motherfucking shit.

29:54.808 --> 29:55.974
No, he's-- no worries.

29:56.057 --> 29:57.432
Honey, come on,
you know how they feel

29:57.516 --> 29:59.224
-about the phones on the course.
-It's Larry, for you.

29:59.307 --> 30:01.182
-My cousin.
-Larry, for me?

30:01.265 --> 30:02.474
-Mm.
-What?

30:02.557 --> 30:04.349
Okay, just tell him
I'll call him after 18.

30:04.432 --> 30:06.140
He says
it's about the school.

30:07.516 --> 30:10.140
Larry from...
the mattress firm?

30:10.224 --> 30:12.182
No, he's over
at Ace Hardware now.

30:12.724 --> 30:15.599
So this kid, he gives
my guy a home address.

30:15.808 --> 30:17.099
In Westhampton.

30:17.474 --> 30:19.891
Full 50 miles
outside of Roslyn.

30:20.224 --> 30:21.766
And it's a home address.

30:22.891 --> 30:25.099
You know?
So I say to myself, I say,

30:25.182 --> 30:26.808
"What's a Roslyn
school's contractor

30:26.891 --> 30:27.974
"doing buying supplies

30:28.057 --> 30:29.641
all the way out
in Selden for, anyway?"

30:29.724 --> 30:30.766
No, we wouldn't, we wouldn't.

30:30.849 --> 30:32.432
We get our materials
wholesale, anyway.

30:32.516 --> 30:33.974
We, we put out bids.

30:34.557 --> 30:37.641
Tool chest, shower heads.
That's home improvement.

30:37.724 --> 30:39.349
-That's not school stuff.
-That's right, right.

30:39.432 --> 30:41.140
-It doesn't add up, Bob.
-Who is this James McCarden

30:41.224 --> 30:42.683
and why does he have
a Roslyn expense card?

30:42.766 --> 30:44.140
I don't know.
I don't even know a McCarden.

30:44.224 --> 30:45.683
There is no McCarden
at Roslyn.

30:45.766 --> 30:48.474
Oh, hang on, honey,
wasn't Pam Cremona

30:48.557 --> 30:49.808
or Gluckin or whatever she is,

30:49.891 --> 30:51.641
wasn't her first husband
a McCarden?

30:52.974 --> 30:53.974
Come on.

30:54.057 --> 30:56.265
No way.
Pam Gluckin, of all people?

30:56.349 --> 30:58.557
She's gonna have a house
on Dune Road?

31:01.599 --> 31:03.057
(engine stops)

31:11.516 --> 31:13.349
-Bob: What should we say?
-Woman: No, there's
nothing to say.

31:13.432 --> 31:14.974
-Woman: The receipts
say everything.
-Bob: Yeah, okay.

31:15.057 --> 31:17.891
-Bob: But we need to...
-Okay, she's right behind you.

31:20.849 --> 31:22.099
Hi, Pam.

31:22.432 --> 31:24.516
Frank: And, uh,
I want to thank you all

31:24.599 --> 31:25.891
for volunteering time
out of your day

31:25.974 --> 31:27.724
to speak with me.
I would just

31:27.808 --> 31:29.099
love to hear from each
of you what you hope

31:29.182 --> 31:30.974
to achieve in the sixth grade.

31:31.683 --> 31:33.224
Yeah, let's start
with you, Heather.

31:33.307 --> 31:34.724
I wanna get all A's
and become

31:34.808 --> 31:37.140
a cardiothoracic surgeon
like my mom.

31:38.474 --> 31:39.974
(chuckles)

31:40.808 --> 31:42.349
Great, uh,

31:42.432 --> 31:44.224
but just for the purposes
of today...

31:44.307 --> 31:45.849
-(door opens)
-if you could just--

31:46.891 --> 31:48.057
